So far as these love-poems are Greek at all, they are like the ” early Greek lyrics, not the latest compositions of Alexandria, and we are left to the conclusion that Catullus is, except in the elegies‚ and to some extent in the“ Peleus and Thetis‚” less indebted to Alexandrina models than is generally supposed: amongst his per- sonal friends Cinna, in the succeeding generation, Virgil and Propertius, show far clearer proofs of direct and conscious imitation)
